reviews.text: An unforgettable experience at Masai Mara National Reserve! From breathtaking landscapes to incredible wildlife encounters, every moment felt like a scene from a nature documentary. A must-visit for anyone seeking adventure and raw beauty!"

There‚Äôs more than one word to describe the Masai Mara, but for me, ‚Äòmagical‚Äô really sums it up. Seeing all the Big Five in their natural habitat, plus countless other animals, was an experience I‚Äôll never forget. Watching them hunt, eat, sleep, or just go about their day was incredible. One of the highlights was having a picnic lunch in the wild! It was such a unique experience, surrounded by nature at its finest.

The game drives were amazing, and the park's vastness and beauty, combined with the chance to witness such raw wildlife, made this trip absolutely worth it. If you‚Äôre looking for an adventure that feels like a dream come true, the Masai Mara is the place to be.

Another unforgettable experience was visiting a Masai tribe in their village. Seeing inside their homes and learning about their way of life was amazing. The people were so welcoming, and it really gave me a deeper appreciation for their culture.

However, the tricky part came when we visited their small market, where they display handmade items like earrings, necklaces, bowls, and more. When you ask for prices, they don‚Äôt give individual ones‚Äîinstead, they say, "It's okay, it's okay, at the end, we‚Äôll calculate everything." This often leads to a much higher total than expected, so be ready to negotiate. Personally, I didn‚Äôt haggle much, as I saw it as a chance to support the community, especially the children. I even gave a little extra to the chief of the tribe, who was 94 years old. It felt so rewarding and was absolutely worth it.
Amazing national park with many animals. Taken great care of by the Kenyan officials. Had a lovely time exploring

A beautiful trip to the Maasai Mara. Saw 3 of the big 5 and many many other majestic animals. Had the time of my life on safari! The animals, the views‚Äîeverything was pure magic. ü¶Åüåø #memoriesmade #maasaimara #safari #tembeakenya

We had a great time in the Mara we were able to spot all the animals from the big 5 to the rest .my guest had an amazing experience  the itinerary went as planned
Book with saddlebird Adventures and you will definitely make unforgettable memories

A captivating park with beautiful animals, most of which are elephants and gazelles. You have to be lucky to see lions and leopards. You can definitely see the sunrise and be amazed by the animals and Mount Kilimanjaro at the same time.

Absolutely breathtaking! Great views of the wildlife with the mount Kilimanjaro. In just 2 hours we were able to see so many animals. Hunderst of elephants everywhere! Definitely a must to
visit!

If you‚Äôre trying to see elephants and hundreds of them, look no further. This arid plain fed by the water of Kilimanjaro makes for an exceptional habitat to see them. A few hours after sunrise they often are moving in big family troops from the east of the park into the Central Park where the water is. Birding is good around the lakes and swampy zones with many different types of cranes, storks, and small shorebirds. Large flocks of flamingos can be found on the shores of the primary persistent lake. I visited in the dry season of February and animals were still way to spot.

Roads are full of safari vehicles which is a blessing and a curse. I don‚Äôt know how a park like this would function without the revenue they bring in and the vehicles keep people and animals separated in a way that is safe for both. At times, when 20 vehicles are trying to crowd around a cheetah in the sun it feels odd partly due to the cheetah‚Äôs indifference and the crowd‚Äôs thirst to watch its every action, but if this strange relationship is what maintains this place so these organisms can exist within the world of Homo economesis than so be it. This is not to make it sound like this is some sort to zoo carved by roads. A good majority of the space has no roads, so animals can find places where they need not interact with humans.

I sometimes wonder if the animals have stories that map the changes of humans; imagine the stories elephants may have of the omnivorous naked primate that once ran the plains and now only can be found on the wide and worn dirt paths in the belly of awkward aluminum beasts that fart diesel.

Absolutely amazing national park. We did a tour through Keshi Tours (and had the kind and wonderful tour guide Richard) and were fortunate enough to see all the animals we wanted to see, including lions, and experience elephants in front of the stunning Kilimanjaro view. Recommend!!!

Our visit to Amboseli National Park was simply breathtaking! üêòü¶Å Exploring the park with my wife was an unforgettable experience, highlighted by the incredible sight of elephants grazing peacefully in the swamps and even witnessing lions feeding on a fresh kill. üèûÔ∏è‚ú® The stunning scenery and up-close encounters with wildlife made it a day to cherish forever. Amboseli truly offers a magical and awe-inspiring safari experience! üåÖ‚ù§Ô∏è

Truly a wonderful experience to visit Nairobi National Park.  We visited on an overcast, breezy morning and the gray clouds overhead brought out the color in everything and the air was so fresh in the park, whenever we would drive to a new area, I would stand up in the transport and deep breathe.  Very invigorating.  So many different animals both great and small, with great views of nature and wildlife.

Such an amazing place. Be careful with the Safari of choice you use as many are going to rip you off.
The animals and the general experience here is amazing. The tour vehicles are busy moving to get the best shot and experience, resulting in busy back and forth etc. The animals are somewhat familiar with humans it appears.

Nairobi National Park is truly a gem! My experience there was absolutely amazing. Walking around and encountering playful monkeys was such a delightful surprise, and being able to get up close and touch the giraffes was unforgettable.

The highlight for me was spotting a leopard and seeing rhinos in their natural habitat‚Äîan incredible sight that made the visit so special. The park is well-maintained, and the diversity of wildlife is just breathtaking. I highly recommend it for anyone looking to experience the beauty of nature and wildlife without venturing far from the city. A must-visit!

I visited Nairobi National Park with four guests, and it was such an amazing experience. It‚Äôs incredible how close the park is to the city, yet it feels like a completely different world. The stunning views of wildlife with the Nairobi skyline in the background were something special.

We were lucky to spot lions, rhinos, giraffes, and so many other animals‚Äîit felt like the perfect safari adventure. The park is well-maintained, and exploring it was smooth and enjoyable. Our guide really added to the experience, sharing interesting insights and making sure we didn‚Äôt miss anything.

My guests were absolutely thrilled, and we all left with unforgettable memories. If you‚Äôre ever in Nairobi, visiting the park is a must‚Äîit‚Äôs the perfect way to experience Kenya‚Äôs incredible wildlife so close to the city.

Had good experience, though wasn‚Äôt lucky enough to see all big four (out of big five there isn‚Äôt any elephant in this park) but I guess that uncertainty is part of such safari - it‚Äôs not a zoo. Booked a tour in advance and it turned out very good. It should be fine to uber to the park, get on a car provided there, but it‚Äôs not too different from booking a tour (my hotel is in the north thus return uber would cost 30 usd anyway). Choose either early morning (mine was 6am) or late afternoon, as locals say animals don‚Äôt want to come out under heat. Getting a park ticket was a pain, having to register on a website etc which took the group (6people) half hour to complete.

I have had only one day safari and it has been amazing! Starting pretty early: 7am I was able to see most of the animals with no other people around. Clean and very big park with friendly staff at the entrance.

Beautiful place with possibilities to se a lot of wildlife but one thing destroyed my opinion. We found a large hole in the ground where people have throw their trash, in addition trashes was on fire...(In National Park) near one of the hotels. That place was full animals but also full of plastic. Cant understand why Rangers allow this.

I did not like how they treat tourists, not very inviting. Would never go back.
You must have a Kenyan id even if you are Kenyan or you will have to pay $6000 ksh instead of $500 ksh.

5 stars for this park. It is the 3rd that I have visited in Kenya.
Don't compare the parks.
They are unique with their own specificities.
Tsavo East is huge with more than 13'000 km2. The sceneries are just stunning, with the dominant red color of the ground, which taints the elephants in red.
You will drive many km but it is part of this park. Go for it...

We did a three day visit to Tsavo East National Park it  was like stepping into an animal paradise! The park's vast landscapes and abundant wildlife made every moment unforgettable. We really enjoyed the game drives, by our guide, spotting elephants, lions, and so many other animals in their natural habitat. The scenery was breathtaking, and the thrill of seeing wildlife up close was unmatched. It was an incredible experience, and we can't wait to go back againüòä
Amazing safari trip. I went with my personal car and took around 2 hours but barely covered the whole area. So many animals were seen such as elephants, giraffes, HUGE zebras and much more

Amazing Safari. In 3 game drives we saw scores of elephants, impala, recticular giraffe plus many others. We also spotted 5 different leoness, one Cheeta and one leopard.
The scenario is wonderful and quite "compact".

This is a park definitely worth seeing. Rugged, diverse landscape with lots of vegetation, small mountains, and the river along its southern edge. A beautifully scenic park to drive around with a multitude of paths you can follow as you search for wildlife. It has a very wild and isolated feel to it so when you come across wildlife in varying surroundings, it makes it memorable trip you‚Äôll never forget

It is quite hard to see some animals here as there are high bushes. On the other side, we found here some of the endemic animals like oryx, somalian ostrich and gerenuk. Also it is pretty far from Nairobi and during the dry season there istoo high temperature.

As compared to Masai Mara, Samburu National Reserve is very much less crowded and calm, you can enjoy the nature without being intimidated by numerous vehicles or rangers. However, there are less animals be it in variety or numbers. It is one of the rare places in Kenya where you will see the reticulated giraffes. Other animals include lions, cheetas, elephants, ostriches, zebras, crocodiles, etc.

Two nights and 3 days can be enough for Samburu but I will recommend you combine visiting other places if you are coming from Nairobi like Mount Kenya, Ol Pejeta Conservancy, Aberdare National Park etc., and spend like 7 nights in these regions. But plan your journey outside of the rainy seasons (especially October, November) and hire a land cuiser for best experience. But honestly its a very very expensive experience as to what you will be able to admire.

Had an amazing time at Meru National Park. Definitely worth a visit and see the rhinos. I would advice to carry enough foods and drinks.

If one is staying at the KWS Bandas, take note of:
1. Checkout time: 9am which is fairly early.
2. Take enough insect repellent and mosquito coil.
3. December time is very hot at night. Plan well. There are no fans.
4. Electricity is available.

One of our favourites in Kenya!
Easy to get around, welcoming staff and of course also lots of animals. Unfortunaly we didn't know that you are just allowed to open the Gate to the rhino sanctuary in the Park, so we missed out in that one. At Times the grass is quite high, which makes it more difficult to spot some animals, but you'll manage. Also great Public Campsite!
Entered through Murera Gate. The park has plenty of wildlife including lions, buffaloes, gazelles, giraffes, elephants as well as plenty of birdlife. Really enjoyed my game drives here 10/10

One of the best places that lives up to its slogan,.... The complete wilderness.

This park is great if you want to have time in and with nature. Very few vehicles during your game drive.

It's also a Rhino Sanctuary.

This is one of the hidden gems of Kenyan fauna and flora. There are vast number of animals such as thousands of elephants, hundreds of herds of buffaloes, water bucks,  giraffes, warthogs, antelopes, gazelles, and many more. If you are keen rise early you are likely to see  lions, leopards, and other carnivores hunting! are myriads of birds like Somali ostriches, herons, crown birds, storks, sterling among others.
Meru national park is especially known for the rhinos. It has a large well-protected and preserved rhino sanctuary. It boasts of white rhino and has the second largest rhino population in Africa.
The are numerous hotels in this well-watered vast wild. I'd advise that you go there with a plan to spend the night and enjoy the full experience of the wild.
The only downside is the road to getting there. The road from Maua town is a bit too pot-holed and rough...but I suppose it is the Safari experience!üòé

The Aberdare Ranges offer lush vegetation and serene landscapes, making it an ideal spot for meditation and relaxation. Its peaceful environment is perfect for reconnecting with nature and enjoying quiet moments of reflection.

Aberdare national Park is one of the best parks in Kenya. The drives here are incredible and the views out of this world. The roads are passable and wide enough for any car. The wildlife here is wide; they will surely have a lovely safari drive.

The lush green forests and the great waterfalls are worthy every visit. For daytrip hikes, make sure you have the right gear. It gets so wet and steep along the trails. Do not rush at all, the oxygen levels are less due to the high altitude.

Do not worry of accommodation. There are lodges and hotels around and also Airbnbs are available outside the park for a two day visit or maybe three.

Aberdare National Park  is surely the best park in Kenya. Better than Masai Mara in my own opinion.
An elephant charged at our jeep which was scarily exciting! Also got to see buffalos on the short trip before we had to make a hasty exit after we came across an angry heard of elephants.

A beautiful park for a one day adventure.
Many animals and a great spot for a picnic at the lake

We go regularly to the park. However, this time it was outstanding with elephant herds, buffalos, a hyena mother with her young ones, a wild Boer, a deer and as usually a stunning landscape. The roads were in good condition and dry. It was a feast for the senses.

This national park truly challenges our traditional understanding. It's hard to imagine that on one side of a small hill, just outside the park, lies a city with apartments and residential areas. Yet, Lake Nakuru National Park, surrounded by urban development, is home to an incredible array of wildlife!

Last November, we saw so many animals here, including the long-anticipated rhinos and a wide variety of birds. It was such a joyful and fulfilling experience, and we are deeply grateful. This is truly a beautiful place, one that leaves a lasting impression and makes you reluctant to leave.

Lake Nakuru National Park is a gem that offers stunning landscapes, incredible wildlife, and a peaceful atmosphere. The highlight is the shimmering soda lake, often painted pink by thousands of flamingos‚Äîa breathtaking sight you‚Äôll never forget.

The park is teeming with life, from rhinos grazing in open plains to zebras, buffalo, and giraffes wandering freely. Bird lovers will be in heaven with over 400 species to spot. Don‚Äôt miss the views from Baboon Cliff, where you can take in the beauty of the lake and its surroundings.

Its compact size makes it easy to explore in a day, but be prepared‚Äîit can get quite dusty, so a face mask is definitely handy. Just a short drive from Nairobi, this park is perfect for a quick and memorable safari.

A favourite national park with lots of animals esp rhino, hyena, lions, giraffe and a birders paradise. Lots to see and do. Plan to start early and spend a long, enjoyable day out. The roads could do with an upgrading. Road signs too should be updated. Take care as some roads below cliffs around the lake have long been swallowed by the rising waters and end abruptly.

A very good park for seeing megafauna and birds. Skulls of buffalo adorn the entrance to the park and a network of dirt roads will get you access to within 100 m of the lakes shore and run you across the southern drainage. We saw a female lion intercept a wart hog, lots of fishing eagles, pelicans, flamingos, zebra, large herds of buffalo, antelope and a white rhino family with a 2 year old.

Visiting Lake Nakuru National Park was such an amazing experience! We spent the day driving around the park and saw so much wildlife. The highlight was definitely seeing white rhinos up close they‚Äôre so majestic! There weren‚Äôt many flamingos, but the sheer number of pelicans more than made up for it. And just when we thought it couldn‚Äôt get better, we came across lions resting in the shade. It was such a thrilling sight!

The park itself is beautiful, with the lake, the open plains, and the trees creating such a peaceful atmosphere. It‚Äôs definitely a place I‚Äôd recommend to anyone who loves nature and wildlife.

details.formatted_address: Fort Jesus, Nkurumah Rd, Mombasa, Kenya
details.name: Fort Jesus Museum

reviews.text: This is the historical site of Mombasa, telling the history of this castle. It has a strong sense of age. The distribution of the entire castle is like the shape of a person. You can enjoy the beautiful scenery of the seaport. There is also the remains of a large whale displayed to the public inside.

Fort Jesus is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of Kenya's most iconic historical landmarks. Located in Mombasa, it was built by the Portuguese in 1593 to guard the Old Port of Mombasa. The fort is renowned for its unique architectural design, which reflects a blend of Renaissance and military engineering principles.

Key Features:

1. Rich History: Fort Jesus has a storied past, having changed hands between the Portuguese, Arabs, and British over the centuries. It served as a military base, a prison, and now a museum.

2. Architecture: The fort's design resembles a human figure when viewed from above, symbolizing the ideal of a "perfect man." Its coral stone walls and bastions remain well-preserved.

3. Museum: The museum inside the fort houses artifacts from different periods, including weapons, ceramics, and Swahili cultural items, offering insights into the region's history.

4. Scenic Views: Overlooking the Indian Ocean, the fort provides stunning views of the coastline and the bustling harbour.

Informative guided tours available.

Great spot for photography.

Tips:

Visit early in the morning or late afternoon to avoid the heat.

Wear comfortable walking shoes.

Combine the visit with other nearby attractions, such as Old Town Mombasa and Mama ngina water front.

Fort Jesus Museum is a captivating historical site that transports you back to the 16th century. Visiting on a weekend, I only waited up to 10 minutes to enter, which was very convenient. The fort‚Äôs architecture is remarkable, and the exhibits inside provide an insightful glimpse into Mombasa‚Äôs rich history and its role in trade and cultural exchange.

While the experience is wonderful, I‚Äôm not sure if buying tickets in advance is necessary, as the process seemed smooth even without pre-booking. However, it might be a good idea during peak tourist seasons to ensure entry.

Don‚Äôt miss the chance to explore the surrounding views of the Old Town and the ocean it‚Äôs perfect for photography enthusiasts and history lovers alike.

Fort Jesus Museum in Mombasa offers a fascinating window into Kenya‚Äôs history, particularly during the colonial era. Situated on a strategic coastal location, the fort was originally constructed by the Portuguese between 1593 and 1596 to protect their trade route to India and their interests in East Africa. Its historical significance is immense, serving various roles throughout the centuries, from a military stronghold to a prison and, eventually, a museum.

### Historical Significance
Fort Jesus is an iconic landmark that highlights the complex interplay of different cultures and powers in the region. After the Portuguese, the fort was taken over by the Omani Arabs in the late 17th century and later fell under British control in the 19th century. Each period left its mark on the architecture and artifacts housed within the fort, making it a symbol of the many shifts in power over Mombasa. The fort was key during the battles for control of the East African coast, and it provides a tangible connection to the colonial struggles and the impact of European powers in Africa.

### The Museum Experience
As a museum, Fort Jesus offers a comprehensive overview of the region's colonial history, social life, and geography. The exhibits showcase a rich collection of artifacts that span various periods, including Portuguese, Omani, and British colonial rule. Visitors can explore detailed displays on the history of the East African slave trade, which was integral to Mombasa‚Äôs economy during colonial times, and the impact of European influence on local traditions and governance.

### Geography and Trade
Mombasa‚Äôs strategic location along the Indian Ocean made it a vital hub for trade, both in terms of goods and culture. The fort‚Äôs exhibits also highlight the geographical significance of the region during the colonial period, especially the establishment of Mombasa as a key port in the Indian Ocean trade network. Items like maps, navigational instruments, and trade goods are displayed to emphasize the crucial role Mombasa played in global commerce during the colonial era.

### Social Life During the Colonial Era
Fort Jesus also sheds light on the social dynamics of the period. The museum delves into the lives of the indigenous populations under colonial rule, exploring the effects of foreign domination on local communities. The social hierarchy, the displacement of traditional authority structures, and the introduction of Western systems of governance are explored in depth. The museum highlights the struggles for independence, and visitors gain insights into the resilience of local cultures and the tension between colonial rulers and indigenous populations.

In addition to its historical and cultural exhibits, the museum offers a glimpse into the daily lives of those who lived in Mombasa during the colonial period. This includes sections on colonial architecture, the changing role of women, and the influence of foreign religions and education.

### Architecture and Layout
The architecture of Fort Jesus itself is a mix of Portuguese, Omani, and British styles, offering a visual narrative of the fort‚Äôs changing ownership. The building‚Äôs strategic design, including its bastions and large walls, tells the story of how it was used to defend against invaders and control the surrounding region. The fort also overlooks the scenic Old Town of Mombasa, and the views from the top give visitors a sense of the geographical importance of the location.

### Conclusion
Overall, Fort Jesus Museum is an essential stop for anyone interested in the history of Mombasa and the colonial era in East Africa. It offers a well-rounded perspective on the region‚Äôs historical, social, and geographical context, with exhibits that bring to life the complexities of colonialism and its lasting impact on the people and cultures of the coastal city. The museum‚Äôs rich collection of artifacts, informative displays, and stunning location make it a must-visit for history enthusiasts and anyone interested in understanding the intricacies of Africa‚Äôs colonial past.

It's an interesting place to look around, especially if you like the history of the area, but the constant bother from "official guides" outside and after you have paid to go in spoils it. It's difficult to just walk around on your own and relax when you are being approached every few minutes.

details.formatted_address: Off Watamu Road, Gede, Gede Watamu Rd, Kenya
details.name: Gedi Ruins Malindi... Snake Park

reviews.text: Mind-boggling and massive. 44 acres with only 15 acres excavated, with well maintenance structures of an ancient 14th century city. It is best to arrive early and plan to stay for a few hours. Take a guide. The knowledge transfer is worth every penny. Carry walking shoes, sunblock, a hat, an open mind and camera.

Go back in time and marvel at the rich history of the East African towns. It's a gem for both the lovers of history and any who are enjoying a holiday on the coast. Gedi town was a cosmopolitan town with trade ties with India and China.

Visiting the Gedi Ruins is like stepping back in time to a mysterious and intriguing chapter of East African history. Nestled within a lush forest near Malindi, Kenya, this archaeological site reveals the remnants of a once-thriving Swahili town dating back to the 13th century. The well-preserved coral stone structures, including a grand mosque, a palace, and residential houses, offer a fascinating glimpse into the architectural ingenuity and urban planning of the period. The site‚Äôs layout, with its network of streets and sophisticated drainage system, showcases the advanced nature of this medieval settlement.

Exploring the ruins, one can't help but marvel at the artifacts unearthed here, which point to a vibrant trade network stretching as far as China and the Middle East. The intricate beads, pottery, and coins discovered at Gedi hint at the town‚Äôs prosperity and its cosmopolitan connections. Despite being abandoned in the 17th century for reasons still unclear, the Gedi Ruins stand as a testament to the rich cultural heritage of the Swahili coast. This site not only captivates history enthusiasts but also offers a serene, reflective experience for all visitors, surrounded by the natural beauty of its forested setting.
Wonderful place. It has three main sections - the Ruins, Kipepeo (butterfly) and Snake place. The guide was very social and engaging.

Very authentic place. We had a knowledgeable tour guide called Hudson who was patient and explained to us the set up of the Ruins with the different houses and potentially who lived there. The excavation we were told was only a fraction of what was still buried underground, which was fascinating to us. We also visited the snake park, which could use a bit of a revamp. The last stop was the butterfly house, which was a bit underwhelming to be honest. Worth the stop over as a morning activity on your way to Watamu though.
Nice place to remind yourself of the colonial era in Kenya. Nice outside views and nature trails. Also has some very good natural shades to shield from the hot sun.

Well Maintained and informative. A good visit to spend around 2-3 hours. Those who have seen or read the Book - Out of Africa would be more eager to visit and check out the place. Have motivated me to check out the movie would do soon.

Start by this museum before going in National Park to understand the story of Colonial Kenya and Karen Blixen. The garden, the house are well preserved.
Two important tips #1 buy your ticket online before to avoid the waste time at the check in and ask one tour guide.
The tour guide is very interesting and will give you a good overview of the story of the place and the Karen B‚Äôs life.

Not a must visit museum if you are not a fan of hers. Just a glimpse into her life while she was staying here. Heart wrenching to see all the animals hunted and killed, used as decorations in the house as Karen, her husband and lover were all hunters. The garden is nice though.
The history and greenery in this place is on another level üëèüëèüëè I enjoyed the tour with Mike, an exceptional guide and story teller. Will definitely be back soon!

details.formatted_address: Kenyatta International Conference Centre, Harambee Ave, Nairobi, Kenya
details.name: Kenyatta International Conference Centre

reviews.text: Ever heard of Kapenguria 6? Yes they were detained here. A Great place to take history students to learn about our country as well as the culture of the Pokot people. Great historical place

It is mostly known for the Kapenguria six. However, this museum has a lot to offer in terms of Pokot cultural heritage. It also highlights the mostly forgotten Sengwer people of Cherangani hills. It has large open spaces and well kept lawns. The Pokot Gallery is a gem of artefacts used in the daily life of the Pokot community. The snake park needs a facelift though.
Culture history at its best‚úÖ

Kapenguria Museum is one of the unique places to visit and learn more about Kenyan independence struggles lead by the Kapenguria six and more sore learning about pokot tradition community. The place is amazing
Historic place for the struggle of Kenya independence.  Founding fathers were detained here during the freedom struggle.
Rocommended visit. Heritage sit. Benta the guide was great

Very beautiful prehistoric site.

For history lovers , you will definitely enjoy the rich stories by the tour guide.

It's actually amazing to learn about our ancestors and their way of life.

Ooh and by the way it's a UNESCO heritage site, declared in 2019

This archaeological site is now world recognized as top 100 most delicate. UN has recently come in and the museum is growing up so fast in popularity as a destination point.
The 600 years old stone walls built as fortresses against cattle raiders probably by Luhya or Kisii tribesman has four homesteads:
Kaluoch, Kakuku, Kachieng and Kakech.
Each homestead has various unique features, and sizes. Each has cattle bomas and multiple gates except Kakuku to the West that has only one gate.
The museum has also constructed a typical Luo homestead of a polygamist. Which is the huts seen in entry.
They also have a Luo traditional granary for storing grains or cereals.
There's a multipurpose Hall on the grounds as well.
The plans are underway to construct a resource center and a hotel on the facility. This is a report we got from the curator on the 7th of October 2019.
The other Wonderful features of the museum is the 800 metres nature trail. It affords wonderful fauna and flora as the habit is so virgin and serene. There is a troop or two of velvet monkeys jumping from tree to tree.
Bird watchers would not be disappointed either for there are hundreds of different species of birds. In the morning they wake up their guests with sweet melodies of chirping and singing from their rich repertoire.
From my visit earlier in the year I noticed a number of improvement as they have recently put up a toilet block with modern toilets.
The grounds have very lush lawns and would be a perfect place to shoot a wedding photo session for the locals. It would be worthy effort to short an epic documentary as well.
The major disappointment is the poor state of the road to Thimlich Ohinga, Archaeological site. The government need to improve the quality of the road if any and many could be encouraged to visit such a museum.
From here to lake Victoria is 25 kilometers only.
Luo culture on display with regard to household setup and design. It is a unesco protected site and a fee is charged for entry. Well maintained and relaxing environment.
Great historical place to visit. Kid friendly. There are nature trials that you can follow and bird watch. Picnic area being put up soon.
Great place to learn about ancient history. Beautiful views of the ocean as well as the snakes and tortoises

If you're in Kilifi for more than a couple days, you should visit. The ruins are very close to town so you can take a tuk tuk, taxi or boda to get there in a few minutes. Entry is currently 500 KSh if you do the combined entry with the snake park. I'm not sure if a guide was mandatory or not but we went with the guide, Daniel, a university student placed there by his school program as a very active internship (so it costs 500 + tip to your guide). The ruins themselves are interesting but they leave one with a lot of questions. As others have said, I hope there's more investment in preservation and research in the near future. It's a beautiful site, with great views of the creek and surrounding forested area. We saw monkeys and enjoyed the giant baobob trees. The snake park was interesting but if you're into animal welfare, you'll probably be cringing.
Quite a small tour with good history to it.
A historical cite anyone else would like to visit while in Kilifi

Very interesting place with very knowledgeable guides... Learnt alot qthe rise and fall og Manarani in Kilifi between 14th and 17th century. Learnt about the old Kilifi ferry and also about took a tour of the snakes in their park.

Generally Sibiloi is wonderful. With beautiful sites.
Kobi fora has been neglected and poorly maintained I was not happy.
The most unique destination in Kenya.
Very educational experience
Nice

Climbing Mount Kenya is an exhilarating experience that combines physical challenge with breathtaking scenery and a deep connection to nature. Whether you're an experienced mountaineer or a first-time hiker, the journey up Africa's second-highest mountain offers something truly special.
The Start: Naro Moru Gate
Most climbers begin their trek at the Naro Moru Gate, one of the most popular routes. The initial part of the hike takes you through dense rainforest, where you can spot unique flora and fauna, including colobus monkeys and various bird species. The air is fresh and crisp, and the excitement of the journey ahead begins to build.

The Moorlands: Mackinder's Camp
As you ascend, the rainforest gives way to moorlands covered in giant lobelias and senecios, plants that look like something out of a prehistoric landscape. The terrain becomes more rugged, and the altitude starts to take its toll, but the views become increasingly stunning. Mackinder's Camp, located in the Teleki Valley, is a common stop for the night. From here, you can see the peaks looming above, a reminder of the challenge still to come.
The Alpine Desert: Shipton's Camp
Continuing up, you enter the alpine desert, a stark and surreal environment where only the hardiest plants survive. The landscape is rocky and barren, but the views are spectacular. You might encounter other climbers here, sharing stories and tips around a fire at Shipton's Camp, the last major stop before the summit attempt. The nights are cold, and the altitude can cause discomfort, but the anticipation of reaching the peak
Summit Day: Lenana Peak
The summit attempt usually begins before dawn, with climbers starting in the dark to reach the peak by sunrise. The air is thin, and every step takes effort, but the reward is worth it. As you near Point Lenana, the third-highest peak, the sun begins to rise, casting a golden glow over the surrounding mountains and valleys. Standing at the summit, you feel a profound sense of achievement and awe as you take in the panoramic views stretching as far as Mount Kilimanjaro on a clear day
The Descent
The descent is quicker but no less beautiful, as you retrace your steps through the different ecological zones. The sense of accomplishment is strong, and there's a camaraderie among the climbers who have shared the experience. By the time you return to the gate, you're tired but exhilarated, with memories of the climb that will last a lifetime.

The great scenarios within Mt. Kenya National park such as tarns, lakes, the huge heaps of stones (peaks), amazing guards and teammates made this hike the best among the few I have had.
The rough terrain which tested on the eagerness to climb up the peak was something else, ooh, don't forget the chilling cold late in the evening and early in the morning and receiving blessings in terms of rain as we trekked the tracks.
I am grateful to have experienced a sunrise while at the top of the third highest peak on Mt. Kenya with an attitude of 4985m ASL. I would encourage you to pay a visit and experience it yourself once you're well prepared physically, mentally and even emotionally.

You get to enjoy the uninterrupted forest which boasts all kinds of indigenous trees and thicket.
We climbed through the mountain, to come out through the nanyuki exit.
Great!

Amazing park at 2-3 h  ride from Nairobi.
Many animals can be seen at a short distance for some of them.
About the birds, it will depend upon the season....
The only grey zone is the number of Range Rover you will be crossing on the way...

Great place to see rhinos, pelikans, flamingos, zebras, impalas, baboons and serenity of the lake views.
We truly enjoyed our day at Nakuru, was absolutely worth the visit!

Park is flooded, less chances of seeing anything or driving around the area. We saw few baboons, few far rhinos and hornbills. I won‚Äôt recommend this till the flood water is settled or the roads have been made to connect to the wild life.

Wonderful trip.  Everyone asked if it was worth going there and the simple answer is yes. I really enjoyed one long day there.  Great climate and we didn't see any mosquitos.

Good choice for a day trip out of Nairobi. Biking along giraffes and zebras was real nice. So is the gorge. Had to tip the guide $20 to let us in the narrow forbidden dead end. Also saw baboons and the rock hyrax and ended at the lake. Day well spent.

Well worth a visit for scenery, geology, gorge-walking, cycling or walking in a NP. Don't miss the Geothermal Spa at one end of the park near the Geothermal Power Station! There's also rock climbing at Fischers Tower. Consider a whole day for all of these! There's not much shade, so be prepared! See separate reviews of the Gorge and the Geothermal Spa.

Had a short visit here. Completely unplanned, so drove to the gorge instead of walking or cycling. This is the type of excursion you‚Äôve probably never indulged in. The landscape is surreal, undisturbed for millions of years. The trek through the gorge was quite incredible. From high, narrow paths to crossing hot and cold streams, it‚Äôs quite unlike anything you‚Äôll have done before.

If you‚Äôre not physically fit, avoid the gorge by all means. If you don‚Äôt have good trekking shoes, avoid the gorge. If you have a fear of heights or aren‚Äôt a risk taker, avoid the gorge. If it‚Äôs raining, or looks like it might rain, avoid the gorge. There‚Äôs a very real chance of flash floods with very few escape points.

The trek requires you to climb, crawl, jump and everything in between. Goes without saying that you cannot and should not do this without a guide.

You‚Äôll get a guide at the main gate to the national park. They charge a standard Ksh 3,000.00. Alternatively, get to the gorge, which is 7km from the gate, and you‚Äôll get cheaper guides here as well.

If you plan to walk, the whole trip will take about 5 hours, so plan accordingly.

Camping is allowed here. Would actually be worth it since the park is quite vast and there‚Äôs a lot to explore.
It‚Äôs amazing place. Lots of water bird and some game animal. You must do boat ride. And if you are a cyclist; don‚Äôt miss biking here. Brilliant trail.

14 Falls in Thika is a natural wonder that simply took my breath away. From the moment I arrived, I was captivated by the sheer power and beauty of these cascading waterfalls. The journey to 14 Falls is an adventure in itself, with scenic landscapes and lush greenery guiding the way.
As I stood at the edge of the falls, I was enveloped by the thunderous roar of the rushing water, a testament to nature's raw energy. The sight of the falls, framed by towering cliffs and surrounded by vibrant vegetation, was truly awe-inspiring.
Exploring the area around the falls revealed hidden gems, from serene pools to picturesque viewpoints offering stunning vistas of the surrounding landscape. Whether you're a nature enthusiast, a photographer, or simply looking for a peaceful retreat, 14 Falls is a must-visit destination that will leave you spellbound by its natural beauty

It's a beautiful nature to watch and relax. Only the weeds in the river were a little smelly. The crossing over was faster than I expected. I didn't have enough time to take photos since the guides rushed us... it's a good spot to connect with nature and for tourist lovers.
The place is amazing to visit with family

An underutilized attraction right on the border between Kiambu and Machakos counties in Kilimambogo area....
I say underutilized because the potential of this magnificent resource on Athi River (one of Kenya's biggest rivers) is huge...

I was indeed surprised that there are not many visitors to the 14 falls despite it's beauty, and fairly accessible location....it's just about 20 kilometers from Thika Town...

Okay, you can still enjoy a variety of activities from just sitting there on the 'shores' of the River, admiring the  beauty that the falls serve as water drops downwards while making a mix of sounds that can sound therapeutic to rock climbing and riding a boat across the river and to fishing (once you move to the other side) so yes, it's worth a visit.

It can also be a scenic location if you're into content production (even music videos shooting).

And there are guides too..and divers (pay to watch them dive) and photographers ..none is expensive...

But overall, I feel that there is a lot more that could be offered here so perhaps the people running it should  look into ideas like offering Kayaking and other water sports....

Also a good eatery is needed.

Then the river is dirty upstream...it appears it carries a lot of rubbish from areas it passes through...I don't know why they can't clean it once it comes in....

Noted that we paid Kshs.100 per person at the gate ..also for the car you pay Kshs.100...for camera the fee is Kshs.500..

My visit to the Bomas of Kenya in Nairobi was exceptional and unforgettable. The vibrant traditional dances, showcasing Kenya‚Äôs diverse cultures, were mesmerizing, with colorful costumes and rhythmic drumming that left me in a state of awe.

I loved the reconstructed traditional homesteads that gave me a fascinating glimpse into the lifestyles of Kenya‚Äôs various ethnic groups. The attention to detail in architecture and cultural artifacts was impressive.

All in all, my experience was both educational and enjoyable. This place is a must-visit for anyone wanting to connect with Kenya‚Äôs rich heritage!
Came to watch some cultural dances, homesteads and tried some local cuisine. Interesting experience and the food was rather nice too.

My visit to the Bomas of Kenya was an unforgettable journey into Kenya's rich culture and traditions! üá∞üá™ The performances by the talented dancers and singers were both entertaining and captivating, showcasing the diverse heritage of the country's communities. üíÉüèΩüé∂ Exploring the traditional bomas (homesteads) gave me a deeper appreciation for the unique architectural styles and way of life of different Kenyan tribes. üè†‚ú® The whole experience was incredible, and I loved every moment of it. Loved seeing all of the cultural dances and performances! They brought me up on stage and I had so much funnnn lol. I also enjoyed learning about the different tribes and bomas styles. Highly recommend!

The entire facility is meticulously maintained, offering a clean and spotless environment. The museum boasts an impressive collection of train exhibits, accompanied by a rich historical context that captivates visitors of all ages.

Children especially enjoyed their time, as the venue provides a variety of amenities, including two coffee shops, an indoor play area, a library, well-maintained restrooms, and a heated building for comfort. Parking is conveniently located opposite the museum, with a full-day rate of only ¬£10.

While admission is free, a suggested donation of ¬£5 per person is appreciated. Tickets must be booked in advance, even for same-day visits.

This is a highly recommended destination, and we look forward to returning in the future.

Fantastic visit. And not just because it's free. Getting a close-up look at all the steam trains polished back to their glory is great. So much shiny brass and hand painted signs. It's very cool, and the size of some of them is incredible. I've seen them before on track in real life, but being down at wheel level and touching them is something else.

We recently visited the National Railway Museum in York, and it was incredible! The collection of steam engines, locomotives, and carriages is absolutely impressive. You are completely immersed in the history of railway transport, from the very first steam engines to modern high-speed trains.

The interactive exhibits were particularly fascinating ‚Äî the kids were thrilled! The opportunity to step inside carriages and see how people traveled in different eras makes the museum truly unique. The main exhibit featuring the legendary Flying Scotsman was simply unforgettable!

I‚Äôd also like to highlight the cozy caf√© and the friendly staff. We spent several hours there, and each of us found something interesting.

I highly recommend this museum to anyone who loves history, technology, or is just looking for an inspiring place for a family outing. It leaves lasting impressions!

Just as amazing as I remember it from my childhood! Came here in 2010 with my family and loved it. Had to return as an adult, now knowing more about the real railways and their history, and its still just as magical!

Wonderful museum, with a lot to see. We especially enjoyed the Wonderlab, which was worth paying for. There is a little play area for toddlers and children under 6, which our son enjoyed thoroughly. The cafe is in the same hangar where the trains are, which gives a lovely atmosphere.

details.formatted_address: Faza Kenyatta Rd Lamu, East, Kenya
details.name: Lamu Museum

reviews.text:
Lamu Museum is arguably the most contemporary museum in the country and definitely the only one in Lamu. Recently renovated with help from the Sultanate of Oman, the museum takes on a monochrome theme as one journeys through Swahili culture, from origins, birth, social order, worship, living and death. It's the easiest place to get a good definition of who the Swahili are, or aren't. The Omanis have taken up the entirety of the first floor to showcase their Sultanate's history, its interaction with the East African coast before and during colonialism, and what present day Oman has to offer.

To be frank, one can see a clear difference between the amount of research, synthesis, story, and art direction that went into the Swahili vs Omani showcases. Despite this being the best for now, I feel the National Museums of Kenya should use it as a springboard to inject more modernity, flair, and detail into all its heritage sites.

Make sure to look at the sign and pay accordingly. Seems a little confusion on true price, and weren't provided a receipt.
However  we had a great time and tipped the musuem keeper to give us a tour. He was amazing I don't remember his name. But he hangs out in front.

If you want to learn about the history, you should visit this museum. First floor is about Lamu and the whole second floor is only about Oman as they donated a lot of money for the museum. Quite interesting but only for 30 min probably.

What a joke!
First floor dedicated to present days Omani Sultan and Oman country.
Try their toilet:
You will be positively surprised when entering!
Ok... no toilet paper.
No problem
Then the flush doesn't work.
Then you take soap from the dispenser at the sink. And then you try to open the tap... but impossible.
So you wash your hands at the bucket on the floor and flush with that dirty bucket!  üëçüòÖüòÇü§Æü§ëüòÅ
I told this to the guy collecting our money when leaving.
He replied that many people told him already before!!!
Wonderful Swahili experience included into this museum.
We didn't love it.

Exploring Lamu and It's  History. Great place to start your journey. The guide was very knowledgeable about everything. When you enter there will be someone there to guide you. So much here. You will have two flight of stairs to climb.  I'd definitely  recommend a visit. Only about 30 minutes.

details.formatted_address: KISAUNI DISTRICT Mombasa North KE, Mombasa, Kenya
details.name: Bombolulu Coast Workshop and Cultural Centre

reviews.text:
All I can say is, WOW! I‚Äôm so glad I stopped by here before leaving Mombasa. This was the highlight of my trip!

This is a compound that employs differently-abled people as artisans. The guide, Ronald, has been here for 41 years. He does an amazing job walking visitors around the five types of art folks do. There‚Äôs also a cultural component of the tour at the end where you can see the old types of homes different tribes lived in, an old Swahili home, and a cultural dance performance.

The tour was 750 shillings and it begins and ends at the gift shop. The gift shop has many beautiful items, all handmade by the resident artists. I found the prices to be very fair, particularly considering it goes to maintain the compound, take care of staff, and run a primary school for the staff‚Äôs kids. In total, there are 34 artists.

You can pay for the tour and the gift shop using cash, card or MPESA. I wasn‚Äôt able to watch the dance because I didn‚Äôt have cash on hand and I didn‚Äôt want them to feel pressured to perform without my paying them. I‚Äôm sure I missed out!

The tour is about an hour or so long and shopping will take about an hour. Highly recommend visiting and I hope to visit sometime in the future.

Thank you ‚ò∫Ô∏è

The facility is indeed a fascinating initiative.
It's a workshop and cultural center where all the workers have disabilities, engaging in a variety of enterprises such as crafting traditional handicrafts, manufacturing hand-pedaled wheelchairs, and dyeing fabrics. The guide who showed you around has been working there for over 40 years, which speaks volumes about the dedication and passion behind this project.

The entry fee and guiding is 750 Ksh. Once you arrive, you should first look for the souvenir shop, which also serves as the reception. There, you'll be assigned a guide.

Beyond just being a place only for manufacturing crafts, the facility functions like a small town, complete with residential areas and a school. This holistic approach not only provides employment but also builds a supportive community for people with disabilities, making it a unique and impactful model worth supporting and exploring.

The best place for unique handicrafts made by persons with disability. You will find the cultural center a unique preservation of cultural heritage of various communities in Kenya and the way they lived before modern civilization
I really I enjoyed since it's a cool and quiet place

The name Bombolulu actually comes from two names joined together; bombo and Lulu, local names for two different birds. The centre covers a large area with plenty of open spaces. It embodies what empowerment of people living with disabilities is all about. Other than giving them tricycle wheelchairs (either directly or through sponsorship), it accords them to exercise their craft and earn from it. As expected, all entrances are wheelchair accessible. The cultural dancers entertain you at the end of the facility tour.
